          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Panama Canal administrator Ricaurte Vásquez next to Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth during a visit to the Miraflores locks of the Panama Canal in Panama City. Credits: Martin Bernetti/AFP via Getty Images</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          US Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth is in Panama amid tensions over President Trump’s declaration that the US is paying for the canal's usage. He said he would work with the Panama government to establish a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-10-04-2025-h1-1-compensation-mechanism?source=website" target="_blank">compensation mechanism</a>. He claimed that China has increased its activity around the canal and controls the critical infrastructure. This is a potential threat to the US's dominance over the canal.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
          The Chinese embassy in Panama slammed America, saying it was using “blackmail” to advance its interests in the canal. They asserted that the US campaign had sabotaged Chinese-Panamian cooperation and stressed that the US had no right to interfere in Panama's sovereign decisions.</p>
        </mj-text>
